&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>Farmers 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>Veterinarians 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>NGO campaigners and industry representatives&lt;br />
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>Policymakers 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>Urban and rural members of the public &lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>Using a range of methodologies, including examination of popular culture; quantitative and qualitative analysis of UK national press coverage; and qualitative interviewing with participants in the controversy, this research will provide a case study of a chronic, ongoing, and divisive public scientific controversy.&amp;nbsp; It aims to:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>understand the underlying roots of the conflict 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>investigate the interactions between cultural knowledge, social attitudes and the ecology/epidemiology of the badger/bTB problem in the UK&lt;br />&lt;/li>
